@Barry Ancona

I don't think that can be because SILENCER is on his list of clues here, and that was from Sunday's Bond themed puzzle. 

Because I hated that clue and answer so much, it sticks out to me.

@Elizabeth Connors

Congratulations!

It’s fun to see that minutes figure as a single digit, isn’t it?

@Rich

"Bolivia has two national capitals: La Paz is the administrative capital city, while Sucre is the constitutional capital."

According to the Internet.

@Rich et al (+ NYT editors)
It should definitely state "administrative capital" in the clue, since the Bolivian constitution directly states "Sucre is the capital of Bolivia" and doesn't mention the city of La Paz once.
Countries can decide what their capital city is, but we can also legitimately describe another city as a certain type of capital if it applies.

@Rich. The CIA World Factbook, the official guide for US diplomats, says “la Paz (administrative capital); Sucre (constitutional [legislative and judicial] capital)”
The US embassy is in La Paz.
Surely sufficient grounds for a crossword, where clueing is permitted some latitude, to simply use [capital] without further qualification.

@Steve L

Until I started solving crosswords again (after a long absence), I’d never heard of Sucre. 

The clue seems fine to me.

@Xword Junkie
I'd been planning to come here for an explanation for BOGO till the penny dropped.  Had heard of the concept of course but not the acronym and shouldn't it be BOGOF? So then I did an internet search (to avoid the shame of posting that the term was never heard IRL, only to be met with several slightly haughty posts with evidence to the contrary.)
Look it up and see if you can get to the post riffing on the Payless Shoe "Buy one; get one half price" promo. Hint: where might BOGO HO take you?

@dutchiris
Been there, done that, a couple of times.  Sometimes yes, sometimes no.  I remember years ago, following a an academic conference nearby, when I was persuaded to go to a nude beach for the first time. I felt like a fool still wearing my clothes, so I took them off, but kept on my disguise of picture hat and dark glasses.  Then i saw one of the conference attendees approaching relentlessly across the sand—I was mortified.  "I didn't expect to see you here!" he said, with a big smile on his face.  RED faced, I gasped, "I didn't expect to see that much of you anywhere!"  He laughed, I laughed.  He went back to his friends and I got teased by my friends.

To be honest, no salaciousness there at all.

@Cat Lady Margaret
Did you get it in one pass through. Meaning once through the across and once through the downs?
A rarity for me but I did today. Giggle worthy.

@Chris

Isn't it interesting how differently diverse solvers perceive the difficulties of puzzles? All your unknowns were my gimmes (I needed a few crosses for SATEEN though), and I solved the puzzle just 48 seconds slower than my personal best of 6 minutes.

However, often I've found myself stumped by puzzles most solvers considered easy!

@Alex Barry

Oh, your Labor Day is not May 1st? I thought it was the same all over the world.

<a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Workers%27_Day" target="_blank">https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Workers%27_Day</a>

@Andrzej
It *ought* to be May 1st, but any hint of sympathy for Labor that hinted at *Communist* ideas was anathema back in the Dark Ages (well, the 1950's)...

September 1st used to be mainly the day after which one no longer wore white heels, which were Spring/Summer attire.  (You were also pushing it if you wore white slacks or a white skirt.)

@Mean Old Lady

The choice of September instead of May was made in the 1880’s, to avoid the appearance of commemorating the hay market riots. Way before the Communists had any power. 

Ironically, at the same time, Europeans chose May 1 specifically in honor of that very American event.

@Andrzej

Great story! Thanks for sharing it.

Mine doesn’t in any way compare to yours, but here goes: It’s easy for me to remember BATIK because when my husband and I got married, my sister offered to make us a quilt as a wedding gift.  It’s very bright and quite beautiful (I would share pictures if I could). Anyway, most (maybe all) the fabrics we chose are batiks.

@Andrzej

Great story!  

And you've painted a picture of your mother over the months that makes her willingness to go nudist on the spur of the moment so hilarious.

